The Boston data frame has 506 observations and 14 variables. The data set consist of information needed to know while looking at housing values in suburbs in Boston. The columns in the data set: crim per capita crime rate by town. zn proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft. indus proportion of non-retail business acres per town. chas Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise). nox nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million). rm average number of rooms per dwelling. age proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940. dis weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres. rad index of accessibility to radial highways. tax full-value property-tax rate per $10,000. ptratio pupil-teacher ratio by town. black 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town. lstat lower status of the population (percent). medv median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

From the plot drawn with corrplot command, can be seen which variable correlates more or less with some other variables. Positive correlations are shown as blue and negative correlations as red. The bigger the dot the bigger the correlation. Here in the Boston data set can be seen that variables indus x dis (-0.71), nax x dis(-0.77) and age x dis(-0.75) have the largest negative correlations, and are shown as largest, most red pigmented dots. Variables rad x tax (0,91), indus x nox (0,76) and nox x age (0,73) all give pretty big, pigmented blue dots. Some variables have almost no correlation with each other, such are for example rm x chas (0,09). Looking at the chas variable, it’s correlation is rather small with all othet variables too, variating from -0.12 to 0.18. Seems like the so called “Charles River dummy variable” has almost nothing or atleast just a little to do with Boston housing prizes.

The scale command subtracts the column means from the corresponding columns and divide the difference with standard deviation. Here we can see the summary of Boston data set scaled. This is done so that linear discriminant analysis would be possible, since it requires the variables to have the same variance.

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

The Human data has 195 observations and 19 variables Description of the data set Origin of the data: http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/human-development-index-hdi

The data used in this analysis consists of various development indicators in several countries and is provided by United Nations Development programme. The data consists of integer, character and numerical variables, where character=country, int=HDI_rank, GNI_HDI_rank. GII_rank and MatMort. Rest of the data frame are numerical.

Below are the column names and their full meanings “Country” = Country name “GNI” = Gross National Income per capita “Life.Exp” = Life expectancy at birth “Edu.Exp” = Expected years of schooling “Mat.Mor” = Maternal mortality ratio “Ado.Birth” = Adolescent birth rate

From the plot drawn with ggpairs, we can see that some variables seem to correlate more positive or negative, compared to others. For example, life expectancy at birth and expected years of education have a pretty high correlation (0.789).
